CHAPTER 3: THE GHOST
The Mustang sits in the darkness like a sleeping beast.
1969 Ford Mustang. Cherry red. Fastback. My father's pride and joy. Twenty years of saving, fifteen years of keeping it perfect. Every Sunday he'd come here, to this rented garage in Boyle Heights, and he'd clean it. Polish it. Talk to it like it could hear him.
Now it's mine. And I can't fucking drive it.
I sit in the driver's seat, hands on the wheel, engine off. The leather's cracked from age but still smells like him—motor oil and Old Spice and hope. I do this every few weeks. Come here late at night when no one's watching. Start the engine. Let it run. Keep it alive.
I turn the key.
The engine roars to life. Deep and throaty and powerful. The whole garage vibrates. I close my eyes and for a second—just a second—I'm sixteen again and Dad's in the passenger seat.
"When you get your license, mijo, I'll teach you to drive stick on this baby."
"For real?"
"For real. Then we'll drive to Mexico. See where I grew up. Just you and me. The long ride."
"Promise?"
"Promise."
I open my eyes. The passenger seat is empty. Has been for eight years.
I let the engine run for five minutes. Then I turn it off. Sit in the silence. Look at my wrist—his watch. Timex. Scratched to hell. Stopped working six months after he died. I wear it anyway. The weight of it reminds me.
Reminds me he worked his whole life to stay clean. Union electrician. Honest work. Good money. Saved for this car. Saved for our future.
And they killed him anyway.
I check the time on my phone—2:47 AM. Shit. Need to get home before Ma worries. She's probably already awake, just got off her night shift, waiting to make sure I came back.
I lock up the garage. Start walking.

South LA at 3 AM is its own world.
The streets I grew up on. Every corner, every tag, every face—I know them. They know me. 38th Street territory. Cisco's crew. They run everything from here to Vernon. Drugs, protection, numbers. The usual.
I pass two of them posted on the corner—Flaco and Memo. They nod. I nod back.
"Qué onda, Mat."
"Nada, güey. Just heading home."
They don't ask where I've been. I don't ask what they're holding. That's how it works. Mutual respect. Mutual distance.
But I feel their eyes on me as I walk. Everyone's been watching me lately. Ever since I turned down Cisco's last offer. Ever since the rent went up again and Ma started rationing her insulin. Word travels fast in the neighborhood—Mat Navarro's struggling. Mat Navarro might be desperate enough now.
I turn onto my street. The building's right there—five stories, peeling paint, bars on every window. My whole life in one shitty apartment on the third floor. Ma. Isa. Me. That's all that's left of the Navarro family.
The building's owned by some real estate company I can't pronounce. Rent keeps climbing. Maintenance keeps disappearing. Last month the heat didn't work for three weeks. Ma just put on more layers and went to work.
I take the stairs. Elevator's been broken since June.

The apartment smells like arroz con pollo and cleaning products. Ma's signature scent.
She's in the kitchen. Still in her work uniform—grey shirt with "Professional Cleaning Services" embroidered on it. Her hair's tied back. She looks tired. She always looks tired.
"Tan tarde, mijo."
"Work ran late, Ma. Security job."
The lie comes easy now. Too easy. I've been doing "security" jobs for three years. Some of them are even real. Most of them are just me testing buildings, finding weak points, seeing where someone could get in. Legal consulting, I tell myself. Grey area work.
But the money's not enough. Never enough.
She's at the table with a stack of bills. Medical bills on top. I can see the numbers from here—thousands of dollars for insulin, for doctor visits, for the prescriptions that keep her alive. The insurance covers some. The rest? That's on us.
"La renta subió otra vez." She doesn't look up.
"How much?"
"Doscientos más. Every month now."
Two hundred more. On top of everything else.
I feel something cold settle in my gut. Anger. Helplessness. The same feeling I've had since I was eighteen and realized the world doesn't give a shit about people like us.
"I'll figure it out."
"Mateo." Now she looks at me. Brown eyes like mine. But hers have that weight in them—the weight of someone who's been fighting their whole life and knows the fight never ends. "No hagas algo estúpido."
Don't do something stupid.
Too late, Ma.
"I'm not. I'm just—I'm working. That's all."
She studies me. Doesn't believe me. But she's too tired to push.
"Hay comida en el refrigerador."
"Gracias." I kiss her forehead. "Go to bed, Ma. You've been up all night."
"In a minute."
She won't. She'll sit there until the sun comes up, looking at those bills, trying to make the math work. Trying to figure out how to keep us afloat for one more month.
I head to my room. Almost make it.
"Where were you really?"
Isa's standing in the hallway. Arms crossed. She's wearing an old Dodgers t-shirt and shorts. Hair up in a messy bun. Looks like she just woke up, but her eyes are sharp. She's always been sharp.
"Work."
"What security job runs until three in the morning, Mat?"
"The kind that pays."
She steps closer. Lowers her voice so Ma doesn't hear.
"You're lying. You've been lying for months. I cover for you with Ma because she's got enough to worry about. But I'm not stupid."
"I never said you were."
"Then stop treating me like I am." She grabs my arm. "Whatever you're doing—"
"I'm not doing anything."
"Dad said that too."
The words hit like a fist. She knows it. I see it in her eyes—the guilt, the fear, the anger all mixed together.
"I'm not Dad," I say quietly.
"That's what he said. Right before they killed him."
Silence. The kind that weighs a thousand pounds.
"I'm just trying to keep us alive, Isa."
"By getting yourself killed?" Her voice cracks. "We already lost him, Mat. I can't—we can't lose you too."
I want to tell her it's fine. That I've got it under control. That I'm not crossing any lines I can't uncross.
But I'd be lying.
"I'll be careful."
"That's not good enough."
"It's all I got."
She stares at me. Then lets go. Steps back.
"When you get arrested. Or shot. Or disappeared. I'm not the one telling Ma. That's on you."
She goes back to her room. Closes the door. Not a slam. Worse—the quiet click of someone who's already grieving.

My room's small. Twin bed. Desk. Bookshelf with my security certifications and some old textbooks from community college I never finished. Everything's clean. Organized. Like if I keep my space tight, maybe my life will be too.
I take off the watch. Set it on the desk next to a photo—me, Dad, and the Mustang. I'm twelve. He's got his arm around me, big smile, proudest moment of his life. The day he finally bought it.
Three years later he was dead.
My phone buzzes. Text from an unknown number.
Heard you're looking for work. Got something that needs your skills. One night. Good money. You interested?
I stare at it. This is how it starts. Anonymous offers. Good money. "Your skills." Code for: we know you can get into places, and we need someone who can get into places.
I should delete it.
I delete it.
Then I sit on my bed and look at the bills on my desk. The ones Ma thinks I don't see. The final notices. The threats to shut off power. The eviction warning from two months ago that we barely scraped past.
I look at the photo. Dad worked his whole life to stay clean. Followed the rules. Did everything right.
And they shot him in a traffic stop for reaching for his wallet.
What's the fucking point of being good if good people still die poor?
My phone buzzes again.
But this time it's not unknown.
Hermano. We need to talk. I'm outside.
Cisco.
I look out the window. Black Impala parked across the street. Cisco leaning against it. He sees me, nods up.
Shit.

I go downstairs. Quiet. Don't wake Ma or Isa.
Cisco's waiting. He's dressed simple—white t-shirt, jeans, Dodgers cap. But everyone on the block knows who he is. Francisco Santos. Cisco. Leader of 38th Street. He's twenty-seven, a year older than me. We played ball together in middle school. Before he joined up. Before I decided I wouldn't.
He's always respected that. Kept his crew off me. Let me live clean in his territory. But nothing's free. I've known that. I've always known the bill would come due.
"Qué pedo, Mat."
"Cisco." I stuff my hands in my pockets. "Little late for a house call."
"Never too late for family."
We're not family. Not anymore. But I don't say that.
"What do you want?"
He smiles. "Straight to it. I like that." He pushes off the car. "I got something. Needs someone with your skills. In and out, clean. No violence. Just... access."
"I'm not interested."
"You haven't heard the pay yet."
"Don't need to."
"Twenty thousand. One night."
I stop breathing for a second.
Twenty thousand. That's six months of rent. Ma's insulin for a year. Isa's tuition if she wants to go back to school.
Cisco sees it. Sees me calculating.
"I know you need it, hermano. I see your mom working herself to death. I see those bills piling up. I see the eviction notices." He steps closer. "I've protected you for years. Kept the crew from pressuring you. Let you do your thing. But I need this. And you need the money."
"What's the job?"
"Can't say yet. Not until you're in. But it's simple. We need someone who can get into a building. Bypass security. Get us access to a storage unit. That's it."
"Whose building?"
"Does it matter?"
"Yeah. It matters."
Cisco's quiet for a moment. Then: "Someone who's been fucking with our operations. Someone who needs to learn respect."
Gang shit. Territorial shit. Exactly what I swore I'd never get into.
"I can't—"
"Your dad would've done it." Cisco's voice is soft now. "If it meant keeping you and Isa fed. If it meant keeping your mom alive. Ricardo was a good man. But he'd have crossed lines for his family. You know that."
Low blow. And he knows it.
"Don't talk about my dad."
"I'm not disrespecting him. I'm saying he understood. Survival isn't pretty, bro. It just is."
I look back at the building. Third floor. Where Ma's probably still awake. Where Isa's probably not sleeping. Where everything I have lives in five hundred square feet of broken dreams.
"Think about it," Cisco says. "But don't think too long. Opportunity doesn't wait."
He gets in his car. Rolls down the window.
"Tomorrow night. Midnight. I'll text you the address. You show up, you're in. You don't—" He shrugs. "We're still cool. But I can't protect you forever, Mat. This neighborhood's changing. You're either in or you're in the way."
He drives off.
I stand there in the empty street. 4 AM. The city's quiet. That false quiet before the world wakes up and starts breaking people again.
I go back upstairs. Back to my room. Sit on the bed.
Look at the photo. Dad and the Mustang and me.
"Stay clean, mijo. Don't end up like the other kids. Promise me."
"I promise, Dad."
I stare at my phone.
Dad stayed clean. Worked hard. Did everything right.
And they killed him anyway.
What's the fucking point?
My phone's in my hand. Cisco's message waiting.
Tomorrow night. You in?
I should say no. Should delete it. Should find another way.
But there is no other way. Not one that works. Not one that keeps the lights on and Ma alive and Isa safe.
My thumb hovers over the keyboard.
Fuck it.
I type: I'm in.
Send it before I can change my mind.
The response is instant: Knew you would be, hermano. See you tomorrow. 🔥
I set the phone down. Look at the photo one more time.
"Sorry, Dad," I whisper.
But the dead don't answer.
And the living have to survive.
